{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488429","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488429"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:41:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:41:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"441"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"441","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/441"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.23,0.15,0.47,0.14,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"441"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116349"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"441","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/441"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"441"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98346"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"32"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1493"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6964"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44861"},{"type":"contributions","id":"47966"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48125"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116349","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116349"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old man is brought into the Emergency Department of a rural hospital after being struck on the right side of his head by a blunt instrument during a home invasion. His condition has deteriorated rapidly and he now has a Glasgow Coma Scale score of 6 and his right pupil is fixed and dilated. He is intubated. The regional neurosurgical centre is three hours travel away.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Temporal burr hole","CT head","Intravenous hypertonic saline and elevating the head of the bed to 30 degrees","Urgent transfer to the regional neurosurgery unit","Craniectomy"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis stem depicts a neurosurgical emergency in a rural hospital and management must take into account the likely limited availability of local facilities and the potential resources to prevent further deterioration of the patient\u2019s condition. A GCS of 6 suggests altered consciousness and extra attention must be paid to his airway, breathing and circulation. A fixed and dilated right pupil suggests raised intracranial pressure from the trauma and the most likely diagnosis is an extradural haematoma. Hence, the initial plan of management should be targeted at reducing the intracranial pressure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESeveral things will need to be occurring simultaneously and the most appropriate immediate action is to gain time. In this setting this must be done by sitting the patient up to 30 degrees and administering\u003Cstrong\u003E intravenous hypertonic saline\u003C/strong\u003E. A urinary catheter will be needed to deal with the diuresis. Whilst this is being done, contact must be made with the regional \u003Cstrong\u003Eneurosurgical centre\u003C/strong\u003E and advice obtained on an appropriate plan of management. A neurosurgeon might be dispatched with the retrieval team.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther targets of managing patients with suspected traumatic brain injury include targeted ventilatory strategies aimed at achieving saturations of \u0026gt;90%, PaO2 \u0026gt;60mmHg and PaCO2 between 35-45 mmHg whilst avoiding hyperventilation. Prolonged hypocapnia can lead to cerebral vasoconstriction and therefore worsen cerebral ischaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAny delay exceeding two hours will be to the patient\u0027s detriment and urgent decompression (by \u003Cstrong\u003Ecraniectomy\u003C/strong\u003E, not \u003Cstrong\u003Eburr holes\u003C/strong\u003E) should be undertaken on the scene - provided a competent general practitioner or general surgeon is available. Depending on facilities available, there might be time to get a \u003Cstrong\u003ECT scan \u003C/strong\u003Eto define the site and size of the problem, but no matter what the CT scan shows, the retrieval team will be needed. First of all, measures must be taken in the Emergency Department to try and get control of the situation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The first-line management of a patient with a closed head injury and raised intracranial pressure must be to give intravenous hypertonic saline and elevating the head of the bed.","Traumatic head injury patients also undergo targeted ventilation strategies to prevent worsening cerebral ischaemia through vasoconstriction due to hypocapnia."],"references":["Reed, D 2011,\u00a0Initial Management of Closed Head Injury in Adults 2nd\u00a0Edition,\u00a0NSW Health.","Queensland Trauma Education. Management of closed head injury: case discussion \u2013 facilitator resource kit [Internet]. Brisbane (QLD): Queensland Health; 2024 Jul [cited 2025 Sep 28]. Available from: https://qte.csds.qld.edu.au/wp-content/uploads/sites/7/2024/07/QTE-TBI-MgmtCHI-CaseDiscussion-Facilitator.pdf","Tintinalli JE, Ma OJ, Yealy DM, Meckler GD, Stapczynski JS, Cline DM, et al., editors. Tintinalli\u2019s emergency medicine: a comprehensive study guide. 9th ed. New York: McGraw-Hill Education; 2020."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98346"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"441"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98346","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/98346"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-28T16:49:37+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T16:50:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"441"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116349"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"32","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/32"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurosurgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"1493","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14